Linux Day 04 – Package Management & Repositories
1. What is a Package?

A package is a compressed file that contains:

Software program files

Configuration files

Dependency information

Metadata (version, maintainer, description)

Example:

nginx

git

vim

When we install software in Linux, we install a package.

2. What is a Package Manager?

A Package Manager is a tool that:

Installs software

Updates software

Removes software

Manages dependencies automatically

Without a package manager, software installation would be manual and complex.

3. Popular Package Managers
3.1 Debian / Ubuntu

apt

dpkg

3.2 RedHat / CentOS / Amazon Linux

yum

dnf

rpm

3.3 Arch Linux

pacman

Since we are using Ubuntu, we mainly use apt.

4. Key Responsibilities of a Package Manager

Install packages

Resolve dependencies

Update packages

Remove packages

Maintain package database

Verify package integrity

The package manager ensures required dependencies are installed automatically.

5. Important APT Commands (Ubuntu)
5.1 Update Package List
sudo apt update

Updates the local package index from repositories.
(It does NOT upgrade software.)

5.2 Upgrade Installed Packages
sudo apt upgrade

Upgrades all installed packages to the latest available versions.

5.3 Install a Package
sudo apt install nginx

Installs nginx web server.

5.4 Remove a Package
sudo apt remove nginx

Removes nginx from the system.

5.5 Search for a Package
apt search nginx

Searches for nginx-related packages.

5.6 Fix Broken Dependencies
sudo apt --fix-broken install

Fixes dependency-related errors.

6. What is a Repository in Linux?

A Repository (repo) is a server that stores software packages.

When we run:

sudo apt update

The system connects to configured repositories and downloads the latest package list.

Repository configuration file:

/etc/apt/sources.list
7. What is Dependency?

A dependency is a package required by another package to function properly.

Example:

If nginx depends on:

libssl

libpcre

The package manager installs them automatically.

Without resolving dependencies, software will fail to run.

8. Where Are Packages Stored?
8.1 Downloaded Package Cache
/var/cache/apt/archives/
8.2 Installed Program Files

Common locations:

/usr/bin/

/usr/sbin/

/etc/

/var/

Linux follows a standard File System Hierarchy (FHS).

